{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18752"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78452"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63814"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10418"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78452"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe electromagnetic spectrum consists of different types of radiation arranged according to their wavelengths and frequencies. Various parts of the spectrum have different biological effects and medical applications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the wavelength range of visible light?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["700-1000 nanometres","1000-2000 nanometres","1-200 nanometres","200-380 nanometres","400-700 nanometres"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct wavelength range for visible light is \u003Cstrong\u003E400-700 nanometres\u003C/strong\u003E. This range encompasses all the colours humans can see, from violet at the shorter wavelengths to red at the longer wavelengths.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other regions of the electromagnetic spectrum:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E700-1000 nanometres\u003C/strong\u003E - This range falls within the near-infrared region\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E200-380 nanometres\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the ultraviolet region\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1-200 nanometres\u003C/strong\u003E - This includes extreme ultraviolet and soft X-ray regions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1000-2000 nanometres\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the mid-infrared region\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the wavelength ranges of different parts of the electromagnetic spectrum is important for comprehending how light interacts with biological tissues and its various medical applications, from diagnostic imaging to therapeutic interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Visible light comprises wavelengths between 400-700 nanometres in the electromagnetic spectrum.","Ultraviolet light has shorter wavelengths than visible light, while infrared has longer wavelengths.","X-rays and gamma rays have the shortest wavelengths in the electromagnetic spectrum."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63814","links":{"self":